http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: A popular Japanese name, Emi means “reflect” and “beauty,” apt for the town’s turbulent history and present floriculture. The region suffered a cholera outbreak in the late 1800s, and was bombed and invaded by U.S. forces during the Second World War. Today, flower farms blanket the hills outside the village. In nearby Kamogawa, the Futomi Flower Center contains a garden and greenhouse with over two thousand plant species collected from around the world, from orchids to cacti. This living hub faces the Pacific Ocean just a few miles from the Tata Communications cable station in Emi, which joins Tokyo to the U.S. and the rest of Tata’s global network.

At the turn of the twenty-first century, three cables came ashore on the rural coast of western Oregon. While systems of the coaxial period usually terminated close to shore, these lines wound inland for over seventy miles, through the fir-populated mountains of the Tillamook State Forest to a Portland suburb nestled in the heart of “Silicon Forest.” The area was granted this nickname in 1981, only a few years after Intel established a research campus there. Yet the seeds of Silicon Forest were planted much earlier. In the 1930s, the U.S. Forest Service Radio Lab was created in Portland, and built wireless technologies to track fires as they spread through the forest, including the one that now borders the cable route. Engineers at the Radio Lab eventually developed two of Portland’s most well-known technology companies, setting the stage for today’s high-tech boom. Hillsboro, Oregon is now home to computer researchers, chip manufacturers, and cable stations, and is a budding hub of data center activity. Companies are drawn to Silicon Forest because of its “welcoming” environment: not only do companies get massive tax breaks in Hillsboro’s E-Commerce zone, but they have immediate access to cheap hydroelectric power from the nearby Columbia River.

Long before Toyohashi was linked to underwater cable systems, it belonged to a key pedestrian highway network. From the seventeenth to mid-nineteenth century, the town was one of fifty “post stations” or rest stops along the Tōkaidō, widely considered the most important of five government-sponsored roads that joined Tokyo (then known as Edo) to outlying territories. While contemporary signals pass through at the speed of light, travelers on the Tōkaidō paused in Toyohashi to buy supplies, visit teahouses, and find lodging on their journeys between Edo and Kyoto. The stations fell out of use when railroads expanded in the late 1800s, but the route remains a major transit corridor. Opened in 1964, the Tōkaidō Shinkasnsen is the most-traveled high-speed rail line in the world.

The Piti cable station, built just down the road from Naval Base Guam, is a fiber-optic superstation. Financed during the cable boom and built in 2002 to land the Tyco Transpacific Network, the building is enormous, though when you enter, the reception desk remains empty, occupied only by a small security camera. You move through a large, hollow room containing rows of empty cubicles, into expansive halls of equipment, and down a cavernous hallway. On one side of the hallway is a giant battery plant in which everything is red; this is the red plant. Round plate batteries are stacked in many rows. On the other side of the hallway is a mirror version of the same plant, but blue; this is the blue plant. The building stands in contrast to the clustered, layered, and remade spaces of Cold War-era cable stations, including Tumon and Tanguisson, further north on the island. There are no photos on the wall, or anything to mark that you are on Guam. The station has been meticulously designed, completely redundant, and has more than enough power and space to land several other systems. The station, like many others, had been overbuilt in anticipation of future growth. Afterward, the market crashed and no networks landed here until 2009. There is plenty of extra room to offer to other cable networks, data or call centers, and digital content companies.

When it entered service in 2002, the TGN (Tyco Global Network) cable between Japan and the U.S. offered the highest capacity of any Pacific crossing. Messages travel along this route in as little as .022 seconds. TGN was acquired by the massive Indian company, Tata Communications, in 2005.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: The first British cable laid in China in over twelve years, the link between Hong Kong and Shanghai laid in 1883 by way of Foochow was a daring leap forward for the British industry, made in defiance of official Chinese wishes and the Danish monopoly on communications to Shanghai. The British were confident in both their authority to act and the technical properties of the cable. Commentators note, “is said to be one of the best yet made, and it has very remarkable electrical conductrosity” [sic].

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: In nineteenth-century Hong Kong, a barrage of undersea cables – from Singapore, Shanghai, Fuzhou, Manila, Labuan, and Macau – landed at Telegraph Bay. From here, cables wound inland across the island’s northern shore, through the city center to the busy Eastern Extension cable office. The daily work of cablemen at “Electra House,” as it was called, was eventful. Traffic was re-directed from one network to another, messages linked local commerce into a global economy, and important political information was relayed about British-Chinese relations. Yet as they sustained the network, cablemen also worried about sustaining themselves. They were concerned about finding healthy food (one worried that local vegetables were not clean enough to eat) and about catching the plague (another remarked that “Hong Kong would not be Hong Kong if we didn’t have an epidemic of something every year”). And leading up to World War II, a cableman recounted, “Life in Hong Kong has been subject to rude jolts during recent years… we had quite a few delightful moments dealing with traffic which poured in for places which had been 'interrupted by bomb.'” Not long after, station life would be interrupted completely when the Japanese took over the island. Today the work of Hong Kong’s cablemen has moved to the island’s southern shore, but Telegraph Bay remains a center of information exchange. It is now the location of the expansive Cyberport, a “creative digital community” built to foster technology development.

In the 10th century, tall pagodas were erected to protect Fuzhou from the “evil influences of atmospheric currents.” These currents brought more human trouble than atmospheric calamity, however, as Fuzhou proved to be a critical site in the contestation and violent defense of British opium sales. After taking China to war in order to secure their access to regional markets, Britain opened the port, then called Foochow, to foreign contact and trade for the first time in centuries. Tea was exported from the country through Fuzhou in massive quantities while European technologies and opiates alike crossed its shores. More recently, the area has been opened to foreign circulations in other ways. As fiber-optics replace the colonial cables laid in its harbor, the Chinese government has iteratively marked parts of Fuzhou as industrial free trade zones, opening its borders to foreign investment without taxation. As a part of the “Maritime Silk Road” the port presently hosts operations from 93 of the global Fortune 500 companies.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: As a key British treaty port in the wake of the first Opium War, Shanghai rapidly developed as a contact zone for international powers. The city brought together a mix of cultures, architectural styles, and social classes, but these connections were made possible by the exploitation of Chinese labor and a concession system that granted foreigners immunity to Chinese law. The first telegraph cable arrived in 1871, covertly brought ashore in the middle of the night by the Great Northern Telegraph Company. In the ensuing years more cables were laid without official Chinese sanction. Without the cooperation of the Chinese people, however, cables remained vulnerable to disruption. Enterprising pirates stripped cables for resale. Local villagers ripped down lines that disturbed ancestral grave sites and the landscape’s feng shui. Men armed with rifles had to patrol the Yangtze River to stop sailors from throwing anchor and severing the cable. The situation was ameliorated by degrees when, in 1875, the Chinese government offered official recognition and protection to the cables in exchange for ownership of the illegal lines upstream of Shanghai. A period of relative stability followed, as China slowly developed an overland monopoly on telegraph lines while colonial powers built ever more underwater connections.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Used by the British as a summer anchorage for the Royal Navy’s China Station and as a health resort, Wei-Hai-Wei was leased to the Queen in 1898 for use in the maintenance of colonial affairs. Although the 1900 cable was initially laid out of a raised concern for reliable communications with Chinese regions following the Boxer Uprising, it also proved to be a vital link to journalists covering the Russo-Japanese War.

Tschifu is today called Yantai, meaning “smoky tower.” In a way, this harbor town was always a critical communications node: the name refers back to the Ming Dynasty, when locals would light smoky fires to warn the village of approaching Japanese pirates. On the northeastern tip of the Shandong Peninsula, Tschifu was directly south of Dairen, due west of Seoul, and straight north from Shanghai. Its central location made it an ideal cable hub during the telegraph era. In the first decade of the twentieth century, ten cables were landed here, primarily by the British and the Germans, connecting to Tsingtau, Port Arthur, Taku, Dairen, Shanghai, and Wei-hai-wei. Even before the cables were landed, the city had long been an important traffic hub: it had been an international trading port for almost half a century and the home to embassies of seventeen nations.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Although Weihaiwei’s name refers to its historic role as a military stronghold (wei), this city has long been a haven from conflicts in the region. The town features a natural harbor, steep mountain surroundings, and two miles of fortified walls built to guard against Japanese pirate raids. However, these defenses failed in 1895 when it was occupied briefly by Japan during the First Sino-Japanese War. After foreign troops withdrew, the lease to the town was awarded to Britain in order to counter-balance Japan’s and Russia’s incursions into Northern China. As a result, from 1898 until 1930 the town was occupied by British administrators and provided summer anchorage for the Royal Navy. Although they kept it as an active port, the British didn’t invest nearly as much here as in cities such as Shanghai. No stamps were issued, British currency was not circulated, and full colonial law was never enacted. This was especially true after the Russo-Japanese War, when Shandong Province was controlled primarily by Germany. Weihaiwei’s cable network, used to relay news of the shifting balance of power in the North back to Hong Kong, provided strategic insight for Britain that surpassed the town’s potential as a colony.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Annexed by Queensland in the 1880s, Papua New Guinea's capital has long been subject to Australian oversight. Yet while colonists maintained a military and administrative presence on the island, they provided few public works or services. The first cables were laid during the 1940s, but were not intended to carry indigenous communications. Instead, they served the Australian Navy. Stretching only a few kilometers out to sea, these armored cables served to detect the presence of Japanese submarines and predict potential invasions. Although the cables were dismantled after two years, Australia continued to administer the region until 1975, the year Papua New Guinea both gained independence and received its first transoceanic cable: APNG. Today, Port Moresby remains an important link in the chain between old and new forms of colonization. Corporations follow in the footsteps of colonial powers, pouring economic investments into the area, always with strings attached. ExxonMobil has begun a billion dollar liquid natural gas operation in the north of the country, creating undersea pipe networks that host both fuel and communications. The APNG-2 fiber-optic cable, one of Papua New Guinea’s newest transoceanic connections, surfaces on Ela Beach, following the exact path as its predecessors.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Oxford Falls is a center of coordination, a place where seemingly opposed forces depend on one another: human and non-human, wired and wireless, and major telecommunications competitors. A relatively rural area north of Sydney, Oxford Falls was a satellite gateway well before it was a hub for wired infrastructure. In 1987, the government-owned Overseas Telecommunication Commission selected this valley for a satellite earth station in part because the surrounding forest, densely vegetated with native species, naturally protected aerial signals from radiointerference. Eight years later, the earth station’s major competitor, Optus, set up a second facility just down the road. As nature shielded human communication and as competitors paved the way for one another, wireless forms also set the stage for wired links. In the years that followed, major international cable networks terminated in Oxford Falls, interconnecting with rather than eliminating the older satellite arrays.

Reusing old cables from PacRim West, APNG-2 links Australia and Papua New Guinea. Because of this project, Internet speeds increased by a factor of 7 in the latter country. Additional cable capacity has been leased to major mining companies active in the region.

As PacRim West’s twinned project, PacRim East continues a line between Australia and New Zealand out to Hawai’i. It was the first fiber-optic cable laid along this route and a major multi-national investment in Australian-US telecommerce.

In 1962, the balance of undersea cable power was shifting from British companies to the Americans. The Keawa‘ula cable station had just been built on O‘ahu’s west shore to land the Commonwealth Pacific Cable (COMPAC). British and Canadian transoceanic lines no longer stopped at Fanning Island, but rather, on United States soil. As a result, the construction of their cable station accorded with U.S. military specifications: it was located underground in a nuclear fallout shelter with thick walls and a decontamination chamber. Arriving at this station today, you see an elegant set of steps up leading up to a front wall comprised of square glass blocks. One transmission engineer describes Keawa‘ula as a “palace.” Designed by a local Honolulu-based firm, the station's aboveground expansion was inspired by a visit from the CEO of Teleglobe Canada in the 1980s. With little space for gathering inside, the staff members at the time held their meeting in a small and cramped lunch room. Afterward, the CEO saw the station workers outside, joking around and hanging out in the trees. In part inspired by the cable community, Teleglobe built a new, staff-friendly environment. The re-designed station grounded the communication hub in the heart of the cable family, yet left intact its Cold War foundations.

This northern suburb of Auckland, New Zealand, has been an outlet for northward communications for more than a century. In 1912, after a new Chief Post Office was opened in central Auckland, the Pacific Cable Board re-directed their cable from rural Doubtless Bay to Takapuna Beach. The workers from the station came with the cable, and the cable station was set up on in the Post Office, consolidating networks formerly distributed across the land. As the cable continued to function without major disruptions, networks in the following decades continued to follow the same path. When the Southern Cross Internet cable was set up in 2000, it too landed on the Takapuna shore. In the cable industry, the prevailing logic is to go with the tried and true.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Carried by a secure, underwater cable from Guam, you land on Glass Beach, named for the abundant sea glass that can be found along the shore. Around you are the spherical radar stations and rocket launch facilities of the Ronald Regan Ballistic Missile Defense Test Site, which served as the command center for more than sixty U.S. nuclear tests in the Pacific after World War II. Kwajalein was a German colony in the late 1800s, then a Japanese trading post and naval stronghold in the early twentieth century until the U.S. took control in 1944. Despite being a vital node in U.S. defense networks, the island is physically small: just over one square mile and nine feet above sea level. Most residents travel by bicycle. And although the 2010 cable vastly increased communication speeds over existing satellite systems, it is also causing the base to shrink. The fiber-optic line allows more of the island’s military facilities to be operated remotely, thus reducing the need for on-site personnel.

Named after its owner, Hannon Armstrong, and operator Truestone, this system initially linked Guam to the Ronald Regan Ballistic Missile Defense Test Site in the Marshall Islands and was funded by the U.S. Army. In 2010, extensions were made to Majuro and the Federated States of Micronesia, greatly increasing speeds over existing satellite transmissions.

Electric Beach, on O‘ahu’s west shore, is named for the large power plant towering behind it and known for regular car burglaries. Three men casually fish off the edge of the point. Families barbeque. A manhole is covered in rusty red dirt. Moving under this manhole, through the cable, and out to the ocean, you briefly pass a small cave with hanging clothes, stockpiled chairs, and collected water. The same beach that makes possible the landing of communications cables – infrastructures that accelerate the movement of information across the oceans – is also a temporary dwelling for some of the least mobile Hawaiians. The Kahe Point station, constructed just north of Electric Beach, has managed to stay out of view, and therefore out of local politics.

To many early visitors, Kawaihae appeared a barren and desolate place. Its arid landscape on the leeward side of Hawai’i’s big island supported little agriculture. Despite this, in the late 1700s it was the residence of King Kamehameha and a staging ground for the conquest of the Hawaiian archipelago. Though the translation of Kawaihae is “Water-of-Wrath,” like Kamehameha, many of the area’s early residents used the water to their advantage, trading both fish and salt extracted from the ocean. Kawaihae’s sheltered bay also brought European merchants ashore, transforming the community into a “depot of goods for the interior.” Cattle were imported and native Hawaiians were forced to harvest sandalwood from the island’s interior forests. The exchange of goods made local resources even more scarce. The cattle ran wild, endangering residents and destroying Kawaihae’s cultivated land. The sandalwood trade brought about massive deforestation. Although Kawaihae’s port receded in importance in the late 1800s, trade has since been revived. In 1970, the United States Army Corps of Engineers excavated the harbor with nuclear explosives, making way for imports and exports once again. Undersea cables land not far from the port, connecting the area to New Zealand, Tahiti, California, and the rest of the archipelago.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Fiber-optic cables encode signals in light and send them down a thread of glass. Although in development since the early 1980s, the conservative cable industry did not lay the first transoceanic network until 1986. The immense capacity of fiber-optics have made possible the Internet as we know it today.

The Southern Cross Cable Network was designed as an Internet-based cable that, at the time, would be the fastest and most straightforward route from Australia and New Zealand to the United States. Just as Southern Cross was being put in the water, the cable market collapsed – this was brought on by a combination of the excess capacity offered by the numerous cable systems laid in the late 1990s. The timing of Southern Cross was “perfect,” as its builders recollect, poised on the crest of the cable boom: if they'd started a little bit later, it likely wouldn't have happened.

When the cable ship Colonia reached Colombo Harbor on February 28th 1923, it made regional news. The expatriate paper The Times of India enthused that “it is impossible to estimate the improvements that will accrue from the new cable,” even though it merely replaced an identical line damaged in the First World War. With peace finally secured, infrastructural repairs were often a powerful symbol of modernization in the changing Pacific colonies.

As you approach Colombo, Ceylon (present-day Sri Lanka) in 1903, your travel guide tells you: “its appearance is extremely picturesque: a fine undulating country, well wooded to the water’s edge and fringed by cocoa-nut trees; lofty verdant ranges tower in the distance, covered with groves of talipat and other palms.” Centrally positioned in the Indian Ocean, Colombo was a key trade port long before the colonial era. In the early 1500s, the Portuguese established a fort and trading post to capitalize on the island’s abundant cinnamon crops. After a brief Dutch occupation, Colombo was ceded to the British and became the capital of British Ceylon. To facilitate faster communication to London, a submarine cable was brought to the island via the Middle East in 1913, connecting to a new Central Telegraph Office in a three-story wood building near the harbor. Messages could now travel between the two cities in as little as thirty minutes, a savings of nearly four hours compared to older land-based routes through India. Today, messages transit in only milliseconds from five cable systems that land in the Colombo area.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: In George Town at the turn of the 19th century you witness the beginnings of a modern city. The streets are lined with warehouses and ghauts, wide steps leading from the street to the water. Banks, trading areas, and emporium stores are beginning to appear along Beach Street. Since its founding by the British East India Company in 1786, the town has grown into a bustling trading port and commercial center. George Town has been built on water: its commercial center stands on a swampy wetland that was leveled and filled in the early 1800s. English settlers built their bungalows high up on top of Penang Hill, forbidding natives to do the same. The settlers’ wealthy Chinese business partners were allowed to build in the middle part of the hill. The cable – part of the emerging modern city – surfaces close to the water, but ultimately connected those who lived far above it.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: In the 1920s, a submarine cable manufactured by the German company Norddeutsche Seekabelwerke and sponsored by the Dutch East Indies government was laid down the western coast of Sulawesi, connecting Dutch settlements on the island to Surabaya.

“The view of the harbor in clear weather is beautiful and animated,” notes an 1897 travel guide to Surabaya. Under Dutch rule since 1743, it was the main commercial port and largest Dutch naval base in the East Indies. “On the water and along the quays great bustle prevails. . . . Chinese and Javanese, Europeans and Arabs, citizens and soldiers mingle” in the crowded streets. The arrival of two Dutch submarine cables in 1913 and 1921 brought the city into further contact with other settlements in the region. But Surabaya’s growth and vibrancy was interrupted by conflict in the 1940s. The city was captured by the Japanese and bombed by Allied forces in the Second World War. And in the 1945 Battle of Surabaya, Indonesian soldiers fought British troops for national independence. This history of profound struggle resonates with the name Surabaya, which some say derives from a mythical battle between two powerful creatures, a “sura” (shark) and a “baya” (crocodile).

Like so many Indonesian cities, Makassar developed under the influence of European spice trades beginning in the 16th century. The Dutch came in the 17th century and the cables began to arrive in the late 19th century, connecting this city with Bali in 1888, Balikpapan in 1905, and then with Java and Central Sulawesi in 1913. Arriving along the cable at the turn of the twentieth century, you witness the height of Dutch development: they had captured, rebuilt, and renamed the city’s central fort. The new “Fort Rotterdam” looked very much like its namesake, with manicured lawns and large stone buildings with pitched red roofs. The walled city that developed around the fort was a hub for the copra, rattan, pearls, trepang, and sandalwood trade, and enslaved local people for businessmen. Although Joseph Conrad called Makassar “the prettiest and perhaps, cleanest looking of all the towns in the islands,” such beauty reflected colonial interests.

“The little village of Donggala, capital of the ‘kingdom of Palos,’ as it is called in books, lies most picturesquely at the foot of the green chalk rocks along the narrow beach,” notes a guide to the Dutch East Indies from 1897. In the early 1900s, Donggala flourished as the principle harbor for the Bay of Palos (now known as the Bay of Palu) in Central Sulawesi. Coffee and coconuts grown in the surrounding hills were exported in large quantities, and various goods were traded by sea and land. A Dutch cable arrived in 1921 linking the town to area settlements. During the Second World War, however, Palu became the provincial capital and trade flows shifted south. As a result, Donggala is still the small and picturesque seaport it was at the turn of the century.

Menado derives from the word "manadou" or "wanazou," meaning “on the far coast” or “in the distance.” The town is located on the far northwestern tip of the Indonesian island Sulawesi. The Dutch East India Company built a fortress here in 1658 and from that time it was slowly and steadily colonized and Christianized by traders and missionaries. The thick stone walls of the city’s fort still exist, but outside it, the town grew into a colonial village with hedgerows, streets, gardens, and cottages. In 1905, traveling via Menado’s first undersea cable, you traverse a busy port filled with large trading vessels and smaller, slimmer pinisiq, Indonesian sailboats. The beautiful bay actually makes a bad harbor: the reefs and steep slope in the sea floor provide little anchorage. Between the cable landing and the distant mountaintops, expansive coffee plantations dot the landscape. Although it will never grow into a sizeable port city, this location will remain important to the Dutch in part due to its massive coffee exports.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Landing at one of two designated sites on the northern and southern coasts of Changi, you make your way inland to a cluster of stations that form East Singapore’s primary cable hub. Today, the area is known for its major international airport complex, which includes a cactus garden, butterfly habitat, and what will soon be the world’s largest indoor waterfall. But this cutting-edge cable and aviation crossroads has a dark history. The British established a military base at Changi in the early 1900s when the peninsula was still mostly swampland and forests of tall “chengei” trees. During its occupation of Singapore in World War II, Japan used the compound to imprison thousands of captured Allied soldiers. (The prison was rebuilt in the 1990s and now has a death-row detention center.) Even the northern beaches where cables come ashore, a popular spot for picnics and watersports, were the setting for a brutal 1942 massacre of Chinese Singaporeans thought to be anti-Japanese.

From the Batam cable station, you look out across rusty brown sand and a dark blue sea. Somewhere across that water is Singapore, where the far end of the cable has landed since 2006. The station shares the shore with many other industries. Silhouettes of cranes and oil rigs rise up against the landscape. Not much farther along the coast are ship-repair yards and ferry ports. Fiber-optic signals run underneath, supporting the large-scale transfer of goods and people to and from Singapore. Part of a free trade zone, the whole area is quite lassiez-faire. The city exerts relatively little control over the information, commerce, and people that stream in and out. This is in stark contrast to Indonesia's policy for cable ships: to repair systems in coastal seas, cable companies have to apply for permits, and might wait months before being granted access.

Constructed through an early-2000s partnership between Singapore’s SingTel, the Communications Authority of Thailand, and Telkom Indonesia, this cable links the three countries across the South China Sea.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: This system, laid in 1908 between the Cocos Islands and Batavia, gave the Eastern Extension company a diverse route from the Cocos Islands eastward.

Typhoons and loneliness were the greatest perils for the cablemen working on the Cocos Islands in the early and middle twentieth century. Like Midway Island, the Cocos were largely uninhabited before the establishment of a cable station in 1901. The station was built at the highest point on the island: two meters above the high water mark, but this didn't keep it from damage during cyclones in 1907, 1911, and 1933. These caused flooding, collapsed palm trees onto the cable station houses, and wreaked havoc for international communications. During quieter moments, cablemen played tennis, staged theatrical performances, and waited eagerly for the arrival of supply ships every three months to bring food, mail, and mild excitement. Today, tourists seek out the Cocos for their quietude and isolation, sparsely and silently scattering themselves across the white beaches and blue-green waters. Floating just above the ocean’s surface, with no hills or mountains, these low-lying islands will face flooding in the coming years as climate change brings ashore ever-more intense storms.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: You arrive at the “Amsterdam of the tropics,” or so the Dutch East India Company imagined it when they built up Jakarta to support the spice trade. Streets and canals are named after Dutch provinces and cities, and the city is named Batavia, after Dutch tribal ancestors. The oldest part of the town, built near the coast and surrounded by walls, is the hub of a far-flung trade network. To the south, Weltevreden is ordered, regulated, and home to shops and government offices. Through and through, the colonial landscape is structured to facilitate the smooth flows of trade. Yet it is also designed to separate colonists from the Javanese. When the first undersea cable was landed in 1859, the telegraph station molded to the city’s organization. The “cable colony” is now “one of the favourite stations in the Extension Co.” – it has a rambling garden, tennis courts, stables, a reading room, and a broad entryway flanked by palm trees. As is true in the rest of Jakarta, the station’s non-European laborers are excluded from the extravagant lifestyle of the cablemen, relegated instead to neighborhoods “in and around the European city.”

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Bondi Beach is perhaps better known as a world famous surfing locale than as a hotspot for undersea cables. Since the early twentieth century, however, Bondi has been the landing point for numerous telegraph, telephone, and fiber-optic cable systems. Located close to the center of Sydney, Bondi offers proximity for cable companies that seek to move in close to downtown markets. The most difficult part for cable layers is getting from the coastal beaches where cables land to the cable station, located in the center of the city. Given the lack of duct space under the streets, it is difficult to pave new paths in major urban areas.

The Australia-Japan Cable (AJC) links the two countries via Guam. When it was completed in 2001, it became “Australia’s largest connection yet to the global information highways,” according to an industry newsletter. The cable reaches depths of over 9,000 meters and forms a “collapsed ring” structure with twin lines spanning each leg of the system. A private company owned by Japanese and Australian telecoms was set up to design, build, and operate the cable until its projected retirement in 2026.
Following a link from Nagasaki to Tsingtau, the Japanese Military laid a cable between Tsingtau to Sasebo, where their naval base was located.

Sasebo became an essential node for military communications at the turn of the twentieth century. This Japanese port is about 100 miles south of the southern tip of Korea, across the ocean from Shanghai. The town had been a small fishing village until the Meiji Period, when it quickly became an important naval base because of its protected, nearly land-locked, deep harbor. In 1898, a major railway station was opened here, anticipating the other traffic to come. Cables came in from Port Arthur, and out across the East China Sea to Dairen and Tsingtau. The town grew up around the transiting traffic, becoming a busy port and a wireless station. Like many other hubs in the Pacific, its connectivity would become a liability in future years. The wireless station here is believed to have broadcasted the message to attack Pearl Harbor during World War II. Four years later, Sasebo suffered severe bombing by allied forces, and was on the list of potential targets for the dropping of the atom bomb.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: When China began to struggle against imperialism in the late 1800s, Qingdao was an important node of resistance. The Boxers, an anti-imperialist, proto-nationalist Chinese movement, had a strong presence in area, and in 1897, the Chinese government began building up a military base here to protect against foreign invasion. Shortly thereafter, German troops seized and occupied this fort. After a year of fighting, China conceded the area to Germany, who re-named the city Tsingtau, a French transliteration of the original name. This small Chinese fishing village was transformed into a German administrative and economic center, with tall three-story stone buildings, wide streets, electricity, and a navy base. At the turn of the century, two telegraph cables were landed, one connecting to Tschifu and one to Shanghai. Today, two major cable systems continue to land at Qingdao, linking the city to Korea and across the sea to California.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: A link between Penang and Rangoon was manufactured by Telcon and laid by the Eastern Extension Australasia & China Telegraph Company in 1877. The cable, 583 miles long, contained over 100 pounds of copper.

Originally named Yangon in the 1700s, “end of strife” in Burmese, the city’s name was perverted to “Rangoon” under colonial rule. Under supervision of the British, Rangoon was built to be a political center and commercial hub, with trade ships traveling almost twenty miles down its river to the Gulf of Martaban. When a cable was brought ashore in 1877, connecting the city to Penang, Rangoon was a gridded, western-style city, with sprawling parks, wealthy suburbs, lakes, and hospitals. The telegraph office was established in a large, four story red brick building with ionic columns marking the entrance. Although the British rule ceased in 1948, following great strife and a protracted struggle for independence, the building still stands today. Myanmar's first and, as of 2015, only fiber-optic link, lands about 75 miles south in coastal Pyapon. As in the colonial era, however, Yangon’s inclusion in the cable system is heavily dependent on external support: it is only one small stop in a globe-spanning network.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Like many port cities in Asia, Nagasaki was “discovered” by imperial powers – in this case, the Portuguese – and developed for trade. In the nineteenth century, Nagasaki became a busy transit point, with a vibrant ship-building industry, an anchorage site for the Japanese navy, and a telegraph cable landing point. Three years after its first submarine telegraph cable was landed in 1871, the telegraph company established a headquarters here, in a large two-story office building abutting the harbor. Within a few years, Japan would build up its internal landlines, and the country would be connected to the rest of the world via Nagasaki. The importance of this station was clear to Japan and its enemies. Described as “clutching the aeortic artery of international communications in Japan,” Nagasaki, as a hub and military harbor, was also a target. The cable to Vladivostok was taken out of service during the Russo-Japanese War, but the city remained undamaged. During World War II, however, Nagasaki was hit with the atomic bomb, the second and last to ever be deployed, killing several hundred thousand people. After the Japanese surrender, the city would slowly rebuild. Old communications lines were taken out of service, and new coaxial cables laid in their place.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Mauritius been a small but important stopping point for traffic across the Indian Ocean. Its visitors never merely pass through – they always leave something behind. In the 1600s, when the island became a waypoint for Dutch ships, generations of sailors and settlers left invasive species that devastated the local ecosystem. The flightless dodo bird and the domed giant tortoise were among the animals to disappear. When the French took possession of Mauritius in 1700s, they set up lucrative sugar plantations and brought in slaves from nearby Madagascar and Africa. And when the British colonized the island a century later, they replaced slavery with a system of indentured servitude, importing thousands of laborers from India. A telegraph cable was brought to the island shortly thereafter, and Mauritius became a stopping point for colonial dispatches between Europe, Africa and Asia. Although Mauritius has been an independent state since 1968, the former pathways of colonial powers have left their mark here: a diverse, multi-ethnic population, a connection point for transoceanic travelers, and a hub for communications infrastructure. Today, fiber-optic networks link to the edges of the island and data centers are nested in its interior.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: While many cable hubs remain concealed, the Melaka landing station is exceptionally visible. The large, sky-blue building towers over the houses in Pengkalan Balak, roughly fifteen miles north of central Melaka. A flag and bright signage mark the gated entryway. Following a series of Internet outages caused by high-profile earthquakes, Telekom Malaysia invited journalists to tour its station in order to expand awareness of the undersea network. A video of the tour documents the beach landing site, vast battery banks, a computerized control center, and the underground “cable chamber” where fiber lines enter the station. In the chamber, a reporter gestures to a bundle of black cables tagged “NOTICE: SeaMeWe-4 Cable System,” surprisingly physical evidence that the Melaka station carries much of Malaysia’s signal traffic to Europe.

When it was finished in December 2005, the consortium-owned Southeast Asia-Middle East-Western Europe 4 cable provided both additional bandwidth and greater redundancy along the bulk of the previous-generation SeaMeWe-3 line between the Mediterranean and Singapore. http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: You can journey to the village of Maruyama along cables from the U.S., Australia, or various sites in Southeast Asia. But upon reaching the station, you may feel as if you’ve traveled even farther—and back in time. Across the road is Rosemary Park, a detailed replica of a sixteenth-century English town. Built in 1997 by British architects, the tourist attraction includes a working windmill, formal gardens, a duck pond, and a recreation of Shakespeare’s childhood home, complete with lifelike statues and time-specific furnishings. Shakespeare referenced rosemary in his plays, and Maruyama is known for producing this and other herbs. While the park looks to the past, the modern cable station is one of Japan’s most popular landing sites. Both enact a kind of virtual transit to far-off locales.

In 2012, a consortium of telecom companies led by China Unicom signed a construction and maintenance agreement for the Asia-Pacific Gateway (APG) cable system, due to open in 2015. The system is specially routed to avoid areas prone to seismic activity while providing additional capacity along the region’s existing international networks.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Past meets present in this northern district of New Taipei City, the vast municipality that surrounds Taiwan’s capital. Traditional Chinese sailing junks are constructed in a small shipyard adjacent to a huge, modern container port, built in the 1990s and early 2000s. Rice and peanuts are harvested by hand on the moist foothills of Guanyin Mountain while a local amusement park attracts visitors with one of the longest water slides in the region. At the same time that Pa Li (also known as Bali) is networked in space through shipping channels and a branch of the East Asia Crossing cable system, it is also connected across time. A museum of archeology showcases artifacts from Taiwan’s earliest inhabitants, unearthed during recent development. It includes a display called the “Bridge of Time,” which allows museumgoers to imaginatively visit a prehistoric Taiwanese culture that once thrived in the area.

EAC-C2C represents the merger of the EAC (East Asia Crossing) and C2C (City-to-City) cable networks, completed in 2007 by Pacnet. Together, they form Asia’s largest privately owned cable system with a total of seventeen landing sites across Japan, Korea, China, Taiwan, Hong Kong, the Philippines, and Singapore.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Before it was cleared for industrial development in the 1970s, Tuas was a small but active fishing village on the western tip of Singapore. Local fishermen would lay palm fronds on the water’s surface above a submerged net, attracting fish with the shade. The name “Tuas” derives from the Malay word for hauling up the net and the catch it contains. Although this technique is rarely practiced anymore, modern-day Tuas pulls together large-scale networks of various kinds. Global cable systems arrived starting in the late 1990s, connecting to the red and white SingTel station, adorned with a series of porthole-shaped windows and a tall, latticework communications tower. A power plant feeds Singapore’s grid with roughly a fifth of its total supply. Near-constant marine traffic flows through the naval base, shipyards, and container port, while waste is transferred to an offshore landfill. And roadways converge at a checkpoint and mile-long bridge that links Tuas to Johor, Malaysia, offering one of the only terrestrial paths off the island.

Stretching a total of 24,000 miles between 39 landing sites, Southeast Asia-Middle East-Western Europe 3 (SeaMeWe-3) is more than twice as long as its intercontinental predecessor, SeaMeWe-2. The optical cable system was commissioned in 2000 by an international consortium of nearly 100 corporate investors.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Built to receive the 2013 Southeast Asia-Japan Cable, this station is controlled by the Brunei government in partnership with two telecom companies. Although it seems secluded, the town of Telisai is well connected by a coastal highway to neighboring districts. These include the country’s largest oil field, which produced its millionth barrel in 1991. Offshore, the Champion Field, which holds 40 percent of the country’s known oil reserves, now produces about a tenth of this amount every day. Follow the road thirty miles east, and you will reach the main cable hub in Tungku. But first you’ll first pass the twin antennas of Brunei’s first satellite earth station, set up in 1979 and visible through a barbed wire fence. What appear to be snowdrifts on the hills around you are in fact silica sand deposits, formed long ago when sea levels were higher. Besides its white dunes, the region is perhaps best known for carnivorous pitcher plants, some of which are used in local cuisine.

The consortium-owned Southeast Asia Japan Cable (SJC) runs from Singapore to Japan, with branch connections to Thailand, Brunei, the Philippines, Hong Kong, and China. Intense demand along the communication route prompted capacity upgrades less than a year after it was built in 2013.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Kitaibaraki thrived as a center of coal mining in the nineteenth century, with rail lines connecting it to Tokyo a hundred miles away. In 2011, a 9.0-magnitude earthquake devastated the city. The closest cable station to the epicenter, Kitaibaraki was severed from both the U.S. and Asian networks, though Japan’s cable density allowed much of the traffic to be rerouted. The tsunami also wiped out an important cultural landmark: a red pagoda-like meditation retreat designed by Japanese philosopher and art historian Tenshin Okakura. While this structure was rebuilt in its original location on the rocky shores of the Pacific Ocean, cable operator KDDI announced the construction of a new tsunami-resistant station in Chikura that will stand ninety feet above sea level.

Since the 1880s, Chikura has been known for precision exercises tied to the ocean. Every year, a knife ceremony is held at a local shrine dedicated to the gods of seasoning and culinary arts. Seven or eight men fillet and plate a whole carp using nothing but a twenty-inch blade and a pair of foot-long chopsticks, honoring the town’s legacy as a fishing community. In 1989, Chikura became a site of underwater cable innovation. The first fiber-optic line between the U.S. and Japan landed here, less than fifty miles from central Tokyo, followed by many other cables in the 1990s and 2000s. More recently, the town has become a surfing hub. Several professional competitions are held on Setohama Beach, where well-formed waves crash opposite the prominent cable station.

You make your way through sludge and silt to come ashore – quite a different experience from the clear seawater of the southern Japanese islands. A Spanish and then Dutch colony in the seventeenth century, Tanshui (also known as Dansheui) grew to become the largest port in Taiwan by the late 1800s. Coal and tea were exported in vast quantities from the natural harbor where the Tanshui River meets the Strait of Taiwan. In 1887, an underwater telegraph cable joined the bustling city to Fuzhou on the Chinese mainland, and a year later the Taipei Telegraph Academy opened nearby. But in the early twentieth century, the buildup of silt at the river mouth caused much of the shipping traffic to move east to Keelung. While its port status dwindled, Tanshui retained its position as an international cable hub. Several fiber-optic systems arrived in the early 2000s, linking the town to points throughout East Asia and the Pacific. Twin landing stations, owned by competing telecom carriers, are situated along a quiet beach west of the city, famous for vivid sunsets and a popular leisure destination for residents of Taipei.

Shantou is a hub in four international cable networks, all built since the late 1990s. From your point of arrival on Longhu Beach, this state-of-the-art China Telecom facility could be mistaken for one of the many resort hotels that line the waterfront. Yet the new technology and luxury tourism of Shantou lies only twenty miles from Guiyu, a town that has been called “the electronic-waste capital of the globe.” Every year, the city receives over 1.5 million pounds of discarded computers and other electronics, most of it from overseas. Tens of thousands of laborers strip cables and dismantle circuit boards to extract valuable metals, but the toxic byproducts of these machines have devastated the workers’ health and surrounding environment.

The Asia-Pacific Cable Network links several nodes around the China Seas. Initially completed in 2002, it has suffered multiple failures caused by undersea earthquakes and structural faults despite the cable’s “self-healing ring” design. Fortunately, the network's disruption has not typically halted Internet access, due to area's many redundant pathways. Nevertheless, the Internet can slow to a crawl when the APCN-2 is down.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Appropriately named Keoje, Korean for “great crossing,” this island is the landing site of several international submarine cable networks, though it is still smaller than the hub in nearby Pusan. As you come ashore through clear waters, the sound you hear is not heavy rainfall but the pebbles on Hakdong beach tumbling in the surf. Named after a crane (“hak” in Korean), this wing-shaped beach sits in a valley covered by flowering camellia plants, sheltered from the industrial shipyards and granite mines further north. Eschewing the discrete architecture of many contemporary cable facilities, the Korea Telecom landing station calls attention to itself with an ornate design. Decorative columns and topiaries line the station’s brick and glass entryway, which faces away from Hakdong’s beachfront promenade.

Entering service in 1997, the FLAG (Fiber-Optic Link Around the Globe) Europe-Asia cable system connects the United Kingdom with Japan via more than a dozen landing sites. The cable, now operated by an Indian telecom, was the subject of a 1996 Wired magazine article by cyberpunk author Neal Stephenson in which he traveled to “six countries and four continents trying to get a grip on this longest, fastest, mother of all wires.”

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: As a landing site for the 1983 ASEAN cable, Songkhla was the first station in Thailand to receive underwater telephone links. Cables surface on the seemingly idyllic Ban Kao Seng beach near the country’s largest natural lake, the same place where invading Japanese troops landed at the start of the Second World War. Years earlier, according to local folklore, a wealthy governor from the south of Thailand was sailing up the coast with a fortune in gold when his ship ran aground near Ban Kao Seng. Stranded, the governor ordered his fortune buried, committed suicide, and left instructions for his severed head to be placed on the rocky cliffs above the beach. The name Kao Seng derives from the treasure’s supposed value: 900,000 baht. Some believe it’s still buried there alongside several underwater cables entering the Gulf of Thailand.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: By the 1990s, capacity was filling up at Hong Kong’s major cable station, and the cable companies looked for a place to expand. Lantau Island, just west of the city of Hong Kong, seemed ideal. It was to be the site for major infrastructure developments during that period: a new international airport, a trans-bay expressway, and the AsiaWorld theme park were placed in what was otherwise a sprawling, sparsely populated jungle. The station builders chose Tong Fuk for their landing, a small village on the island’s southern shore. When they went to construct the station, however, the village leaders resisted, worried that the cable stations would disrupt the feng shui of the land and bring them bad fortune. The stations were ultimately placed there, but companies careful not to infringe upon the nearby shrine.

The landing site at Ban Pak Bara in Satun province is Thailand’s only cable hub on the west coast and thus handles much of the country’s signal traffic to Europe and the Middle East. Yet the area was linked to the global network only recently, in the late 1990s, when the FLAG cable project negotiated for a new station to be built on Thai shores. From Ban Pak Bara, the cable layers pioneered an extensive route overland to the historical landing at Songkhla, directly linking submarine networks in the Andaman Sea and Gulf of Thailand for the first time. Although a key international node, the station remains overshadowed by its natural surroundings. From your landing place on the white sand beaches of this small fishing and agricultural community, you can see modest cinderblock communications buildings and towers across the road, surrounded by acres of mangrove trees. And looking back from where you came, your view is dominated by the lush and mountainous islands of Mu Ko Phetra National Park rising out of the water.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: This Korean city has long been a hub for Japanese connections. In the nineteenth century it served as Japanese merchants’ primary access point to Asian trade networks. When it opened, Busan’s Japanese-run telegraph station became an equally important gateway. It handled all Korean telegraph traffic until an overland link to Seoul was completed in 1888, and it allowed Japanese-language telegrams to leave the country for the first time. Cable traffic spiked from a few thousand messages sent between the two countries in 1884 to some 430,000 — the vast majority in Japanese. In 1931, Busan was the site of Japanese experiments for another communications revolution: the use of undersea cables for voice transmission. Today, the city’s two cable stations, which provide a major gateway to the Internet, are finally operated by Korean companies. Yet the country faces another challenge at its shores – from local aquaculture rather than foreign powers. Dense seaweed forests immediately off Busan’s coast twist around ropes bordering the cable’s path. Harvesting the seaweed, fishermen come dangerously close to the country’s international communications lines. Whenever cable companies land a new system, they have to be careful not to disturb the fragile seaweed’s growth. Each cable must be carefully placed in a “mattress” before it is lowered down into the crop.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: You arrive at a cable station fit for a king. Constructed for the landing of a new fiber-optic network, one cable industry leader recalls that the Tungku station was “built as a palace” so that it could be inaugurated by the Sultan of Brunei. In the following years, the massive station would become a hub of links to Singapore, Malaysia, and the Philippines, followed by connections reaching as far as the U.S. and Western Europe. When a link to the Asia-America Gateway in 2009 created an oversupply of bandwidth, the Brunei government sold it to international carriers in order to finance new cable landings. Located a few miles north of the capital, the station is at once remote and central, surrounded by trees but also a highway exchange and the campuses of both the University of Brunei and an international boarding school. Across the street, a fifteen-story glass office tower (and the second tallest building in the country) contains the headquarters of local telecom provider DataStream Technology Group. When cables first arrived on nearby Tungku Beach in the 1990s, illegal sand mining had caused severe erosion. But the jagged shoreline has been restored and is now a popular place for watching sunsets.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: The Telekom Malysia (TM) cable landing station at Mersing is situated on an otherwise undeveloped beach roughly six miles south of the town center. Large signage on a curved, blue glass awning and a flag bearing the TM logo ensure that the site is highly visible from the coastal highway that passes nearby. Since the late 1990s, it has housed cables linking southeastern Malaysia to the rest of Asia, the U.S., the Middle East, and Western Europe. On their journey east, these cables intersect the offshore Seribuat Archipelago, for which Mersing’s ferry terminal is the main point of departure. As Malays, tourists, and communication signals are carried out to sea, north-south trade routes link Mersing to the rest of the Malay Peninsula as a site of tin, rubber, and palm oil production.

Asia-America Gateway (AAG), opened in 2009, was the first high-bandwidth optical cable to provide a direct link between Southeast Asia and California (via the Philippines, Guam, and Hawai'i). Positioned further south than other trans-Pacific routes, AAG avoids the seismically active areas near Taiwan where earthquakes are known to cause cable disruptions.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: The modern two-story cable station and data center, built to withstand severe weather, sits across the road from a rocky beach in the quiet suburb of Sopu, due west of central Nuku’alofa. Between 1978 and 2013, when a fiber-optic link to Fiji was completed, Tonga relied entirely on satellite connections. Internet access was slow, expensive, and used by less than a fifth of the population. But with a capacity six thousand times greater than satellite, the cable is set to lower costs and stimulate business investment, bringing more of the country online than ever before. Although it entered the underwater network only recently, Nuku’alofa has long been a regional hub. The deep natural harbor bounded by coral reefs is still Tonga’s main port and a gateway to the rest of the archipelago. Not far from the sleek landing station, the reefs are littered with the rusted hulls of old fishing vessels carried ashore by past storms.

This cable, which links Tonga to Fiji and the entire Southern Cross trans-Pacific network, was completed in August 2013 with major funding from the Asian Development Bank and World Bank. Run by the government-owned Tonga Cable Limited, it is part of a larger effort to connect smaller island nations in the Pacific.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: For decades, Taiwan’s cables have been concentrated at its northern and southern tips. While the Tanshui and Toucheng stations are on the fringes of Taipei, the Chunghwa Telecom station is located in the rural southern township of Fangshan. Most traffic to Southeast Asia, whether from Taiwan, East Asia, or North America, passes through the Bashi Strait, the narrow passage separating Taiwan and the Philippines. Fangshan was the ideal gateway to this route until recently, when a spate of natural disasters severed numerous cable links. An earthquake in September 1999 broke Taiwan’s terrestrial backbone, one undersea cable, and caused cell sites and radio relays to collapse. During the 2006 Hengchun earthquake, submarine landslides took out nine undersea links. Most recently, Typhoon Morakot disrupted six international cables and 1,700 wireless base stations, in addition to taking 500 lives. Fangshan, perched on the edge of the Bashi Strait, is no longer a popular interconnection point for undersea traffic.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Shima is a major hub with connections to five active international cable networks and three different cable stations, but it remains largely invisible to local residents. While cables are hidden, several festivals call attention to the surrounding ocean, known for its abundant marine life since at least the eighth century. Every June, a twenty-foot wooden spiny lobster is paraded through the city streets to encourage a bountiful harvest season. And in September, four men carry an oversized waraji (traditional straw sandal) into the ocean, setting it adrift. This ritual is designed to ward off Dandarabocchi, a mythological giant so large that his footsteps create lakes. Afterwards, spectators gather on the beach for dancing and a fireworks display.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: In 2008, Qingdao hosted the sailing regatta for the Beijing Olympic Games. Teams from forty countries navigated a racecourse in the Yellow Sea, not far from where underwater cables surface in Fushan Bay. To realize its vision of a “Broadband Olympics,” China Netcom extended the East Asia Crossing cable to its Qingdao landing station at the same time. While the Olympics may have prompted this connection, there are other reasons to bring cables here. China’s northernmost hub, Qingdao lies midway between the financial centers of Beijing and Shanghai. Compared to hubs in South China, it offers more direct access to networks spanning Korea, Japan, and the United States. Even in the colonial era, the port was coveted for its strategic location. Germany kept a naval base outside the city, then called Tsingtau, until Japan seized control at the start of World War I.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: The Matrix Cable System lands on the unlikely shores of Pantai Mutiara, an artificial peninsula that hosts some of Jakarta’s most extravagant luxury housing and amenities. Inspired by Australia’s Gold Coast, each of the homes in the Pantai Mutiara complex offers its own private boat dock with a canal to the ocean. As a gated satellite town, it also provides residents local access to hospitals, mega-malls, two golf courses, and the international airport. Not unintentionally, this serves to minimize their interactions with the rest of the city, especially the many “kampongs,” or indigenous neighborhoods. In order to secure waterfront property, Matrix Cable System had to buy and convert a beach-area condo to house their cable station, which then helped them to blend in with their surroundings. Despite the expensive real estate, the insular nature of the neighborhood and its jutting projection far into the reclaimed sea make it an ideal pathway for a cable landing.
